{"title_page": "Richard M. Blatchford", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{For|the New York attorney born in 1798|Richard M. Blatchford (attorney)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Richard M. Blatchford\n| image         = Richard Milford Blatchford (US Army General).jpg\n| caption       = Richard M. Blatchford, {{circa|1895\u20131900}}\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1859|8|17}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1934|8|31|1859|8|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Fort Hamilton]], New York, US\n| death_place   = San Francisco, California, US\n| placeofburial = [[San Francisco National Cemetery]]\n| allegiance    = {{US}}\n| branch        = {{Army|United States}}\n| serviceyears  = 1883\u20131922\n| rank          = [[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Major General (United States)|Major General]]\n| servicenumber =\n| unit          = [[Infantry Branch (United States)|U.S. Army Infantry Branch]]\n| commands      = {{ubl\n  | [[11th Infantry Regiment (United States)|11th Infantry Regiment]]\n  | [[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|12th Infantry Regiment]]\n  | Army School of Musketry\n  | [[Services of Supply, American Expeditionary Forces|Line of Communications]], [[American Expeditionary Forces]]\n  | 158th [[152d Depot Brigade (United States)#Purpose|Depot Brigade]]\n  | [[Panama Canal Department]]\n  | [[Presidio of San Francisco]]\n  | 8th Infantry Brigade and [[Fort Lewis|Camp Lewis]]\n  | 5th Infantry Brigade and [[Vancouver Barracks]]\n  }}\n| battles       = [[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br/>[[World War I]] ([[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]])\n| awards        =\n| spouse        = {{ubl\n  | {{Marriage|Natalie Cary Green|1887|1913}}\n  | {{Marriage|Elinor Hall|1921|1934}}\n  }}\n| relations     = {{ubl\n  | [[Samuel Blatchford (university president)|Samuel Blatchford]] (great-grandfather)\n  | [[Richard M. Blatchford (attorney)|Richard Milford Blatchford]] (great-uncle)\n  | [[Samuel Blatchford]] (cousin)\n}} }}\n\n'''Richard Milford Blatchford''' (August 17, 1859 \u2013 August 31, 1934) was a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] [[General of the Army (United States)|general]] who served in the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] and [[World War I]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nRichard Milford Blatchford was born at [[Fort Hamilton]], [[New York (state)|New York]] on August 17, 1859,<ref name=davis/><ref name=memorial/> He was the son of Samuel T. Blatchford (1822\u20131886) and Agnes Leadbeater Blatchford (1824\u20131911),<ref name=memorial/> and his ancestors had come from Devonshire, England in the eighteenth century.<ref name=davis/> His great-grandfather was Reverend [[Samuel Blatchford (university president)|Samuel Blatchford]], his great-uncle was the New York attorney [[Richard M. Blatchford (attorney)|Richard Milford Blatchford]], and the U.S. Supreme Court Justice [[Samuel Blatchford]] was a cousin.<ref name=memorial/>\n\nHe was educated at [[Williston Seminary]] in Massachusetts and [[Claverack College]] in New York, and graduated from [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] with the class of 1882.<ref name=davis/>  He was also a graduate of the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College|Infantry and Cavalry School]] at [[Fort Leavenworth]], and of the [[United States Army War College|U.S. Army War College]], then in Washington, D.C.<ref name=arms/>\n\n==Military career==\nBlatchford was commissioned in the [[United States Army]] directly from civil life and appointed as a [[Second lieutenant (United States)|second lieutenant]] in October 1883.<ref name=hist-reg/> With the [[11th Infantry Regiment (United States)|11th Infantry Regiment]], Blatchford served on the American frontier in [[Dakota Territory]], [[Kansas]], and [[Arizona]].\n\n[[File:Colonel R.M. Blatchford, 1915.png|thumb|left|Colonel Blatchford, {{circa|1915}} ]]\nHe became a [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] on April 26, 1898, during the first days of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]].<ref name=davis/> Following two tours of duty in [[Puerto Rico]], he served in the [[Philippines]] from 1901 to 1904, both in the field and in [[garrison]],<ref name=Hubert/> with the 28th, 11th, and 6th Regiments.<ref name=davis/>\n\nAfter a brief tour as a recruiter in New York, Blatchford was an instructor and inspector for the Missouri National Guard.<ref name=davis/> However, he had served with the 11th Infantry Regiment almost continuously while rising through the ranks, and in April 1913, he became a [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] and was given command of the regiment in [[Texas City, Texas]].<ref name=arms/><ref name=davis/>\n\nIn 1914, Blatchford was assigned to command the [[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|12th Infantry Regiment]], then stationed in the [[San Francisco Presidio]].<ref name=arms/> Blatchford's regiment, a part of the Eighth Brigade under Brigadier General [[John J. Pershing]], included 700 enlisted men and 30 commissioned officers.<ref name=Stanford/>  In April 1914, while on training maneuvers near [[Stanford University]],<ref name=Stanford/> Blatchford received orders for his regiment to travel with Pershing by rail to [[El Paso, Texas]], where Pershing assembled the Eighth Brigade to guard the Mexican border.<ref name=ElPasoHerald/> The regiment was later stationed at [[Nogales, Arizona]], where Blatchford made arrangements for Pershing's peace conference on August 29, 1914 with Mexican generals [[Pancho Villa]] and [[\u00c1lvaro Obreg\u00f3n]].<ref name=White/><ref name=Eppinga/><ref name=Clendenen/> \n\nWhile commanding the 12th, Blatchford organized a regimental school of musketry at the Presidio.<ref name=arms/> By late 1915, Colonel Blatchford had been detailed as commandant of the Army's School of Musketry (today's [[Infantry School]]) at [[Fort Sill]], Oklahoma,<ref name=arms/> and held that position in April 1917 at the time of America's entry into World War I.\n\nOn May 15, 1917, Blatchford was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] in the [[History of the United States Army#World War I|National Army]].<ref name=davis/> He sailed for France in July 1917 to observe trench warfare and Allied training methods, and on July 25 he was appointed commanding general of the [[Services of Supply, American Expeditionary Forces|Line of Communications]], part of the [[American Expeditionary Forces]].<ref name=\"Hubert\"/> On August 5, 1917, he received a promotion to [[Major general (United States)|major general]] in the National Army.<ref name=davis/> Blatchford failed to organize a functioning line of communication in France, resulting in inadequate transport of supplies to U.S. troops.<ref name=Cooke/><ref name=Hagood/> Unhappy with his performance, Pershing decided to replace Blatchford with [[Francis Joseph Kernan|Francis Kernan]].<ref name=Cooke/><ref name=Hagood/> After being relieved of his command in Paris, Blatchford took charge of billeting at [[Neufch\u00e2teau, Vosges|Neufch\u00e2teau]].<ref name=Hagood/> According to General [[Johnson Hagood (general)|Johnson Hagood]], this job \"certainly did not warrant a special headquarters with a major general in command,\" but Blatchford maintained a large staff for allocating billets and office space, including a colonel in charge of constructing new buildings.<ref name=Cooke/><ref name=Hagood/>\n\nIn November 1917, Pershing sent Blatchford back to America,<ref name=davis/><ref name=Smythe/> due to lack of competence.<ref name=Lacey/> To spare his feelings and reputation, Pershing told him that he was needed to train a combat unit and then lead it to France to take part in the fighting.<ref name=Lacey/> Blatchford later viewed the removal as a stain on his career, and he pursued the matter with Pershing after the war.<ref name=Lacey/> In response, Pershing wrote that Blatchford's performance had in fact been unsatisfactory, and that their \"lifelong friendship\" had caused Pershing to refrain from telling him so at the time.<ref name=Lacey/>\n\nDespite being replaced as head of the Line of Communications, Blatchford's career flourished after his return from France.<ref name=davis/> He briefly commanded the 158th [[152d Depot Brigade (United States)#Purpose|Depot Brigade]] at [[Camp Sherman, Ohio]] (1917\u20131918), before taking command of the [[Panama Canal Department]].<ref name=davis/> He remained in command at the [[Panama Canal Zone]] through 1919, continuing after the end of the war.<ref name=davis/> He later commanded the [[Presidio of San Francisco]] (1920\u20131921), 8th Infantry Brigade and [[Fort Lewis|Camp Lewis]] (1921), and 5th Infantry Brigade and [[Vancouver Barracks]] (1921\u20131922).<ref name=davis/>\n\nHe retired on December 1, 1922 with his permanent rank of brigadier general.<ref name=White/>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1930, Congress passed legislation allowing the temporary generals of World War I to retire at the highest rank they had held, and Blatchford was promoted to major general on the retired list.<ref name=White/>\n\nBlatchford died on August 31, 1934 in San Francisco.<ref name=Hubert/> He had no children by either of his two marriages.<ref name=davis/>\n\n{{USS|General R. M. Blatchford|AP-153}}, launched in 1944 and named in his honor, was a [[General G. O. Squier-class transport|''General G. O. Squier''-class]] [[troopship|transport ship]] for the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] in [[World War II]].<ref name=Hubert/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=ElPasoHerald>{{cite news |title=More Troops En Route to El Paso \u2013 Gen. Pershing and Three Regiments of Infantry Are Speeding South Toward the Border, Having Left San Francisco Thursday Night; Brigade Will Aid in Guarding Border |newspaper=El Paso Herald |date=April 24, 1914 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/42886213/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |url-access=subscription |quote=On their way to the Mexican border, about 3000 officers and men of the Eighth brigade of infantry are today speeding toward the border on special trains under the command of Brig. Gen. John J. Pershing. The brigade comprises the 16th [and] Sixth infantry... and the 12th infantry, commanded by Col. Richard M. Blatchford. ... Pershing, with the Sixth and 12th infantry, goes to El Paso, Texas, over the Southern Pacific. ... The brigade is to assemble at El Paso and then report to Gen. Tasker H. Bliss. The Sixth and 16th regiments left the Presidio Thursday night, picking up the 12th regiment at Palo Alto, Calif., about 30 miles south of here. }}</ref>\n<ref name=Smythe>{{cite book |last=Smythe |first=Donald |title=Pershing: General of the Armies |url={{GBurl|jjrcAAAAMAAJ|p=68|q=Blatchford}} |year=1986 |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=978-0-253-34381-9 |page=68 }}</ref>\n<ref name=Stanford>{{cite book |title=The Stanford Quad |volume=Vol. 22 |year=1915 |publisher=Stanford University |page=73 |url={{GBurl|uAcuAAAAIAAJ|dq=editions%3ASTANFORD36105012248097|q=blatchford|p=73}} }}</ref>\n<ref name=Clendenen>{{cite book |first=Clarence C. |last=Clendenen |authorlink=Clarence C. Clendenen |title=The United States and Pancho Villa: A Study in Unconventional Diplomacy |url={{GBurl|T4B6AAAAMAAJ|p=111|q=blatchford}} |year=1961 |publisher=American Historical Association |page=111 }}</ref>\n<ref name=Eppinga>{{cite book |last=Eppinga |first=Jane |title=Nogales: Life and Times on the Frontier |url={{GBurl|QFPYGtLXaB0C|p=105}} |year=2002 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=978-0-7385-2405-4 |page=105 }}</ref>\n<ref name=Lacey>{{cite book |last=Lacey |first=Jim |title=Pershing: A Biography |url={{GBurl|FFCAHW7vcWkC|p=118}} |year=2008 |publisher=St. Martin's Press |isbn=978-0-230-61270-9 |page=118 }}</ref>\n<ref name=Hagood>{{cite book |last=Hagood |first=Johnson |authorlink=Johnson Hagood (general) |title=The Services of Supply: A Memoir of the Great War |year=1927 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |url=https://archive.org/stream/servicesofsupply00john#page/50/mode/2up |pages=43\u201350 }}</r